commText: SRH finish their final match at home with a defeat. They've won just 1 game here all season and find themselves right at the bottom of the table. But they might yet have a say in this playoffs race as they go to Mumbai next. RCB don't need to worry about that right now, with their destiny in their own hands. And what a night it's going to be at the Chinnaswamy against table-toppers Gujarat Titans. That will also be the final league match of the season. If they had lost today, CSK and LSG would've qualified. But as it stands, the three playoffs spots are still up for grabs. That's all from us here. This is Sagar Chawla signing off on behalf of Harish and Kumar Abhisekh Das. Goodnight!

B0$ Quite special considering the magnitude of the game. Thought SRH got a very good score. Ball was gripping as well. We wanted a good solid start. Didn't expect to be 172/0. But that's how well Faf and me have played this season. Faf's been on a different level. I've had a quiet couple of games. The way I was hitting in the nets wasn't transitioning into the middle in the last 2-3 matches. Wanted to make an impact and my intent was to go after the bowlers from ball 1 - something I've done through the season. There was a dip but I wanted to pick my game up at the right time. Never look at past records (not great numbers against SRH). B1$ I don't give myself enough credit sometimes because I put myself under so much stress already. I don't care what anyone says on the outside. That's their opinion. When you're in that situation yourself, you know how to win games of cricket. I've done that over a long period of time. It's not like when I play I don't win games for my team. It's playing the situation that I take pride in. I've never been a guy who plays so many fancy shots - was having a chat with Aiden as well. We have to play 12 months of the year. B2$ When I can make an impact in an important game, it gives me confidence, it gives the team confidence. I think it's the tattoos (secret behind partnership with Faf). We almost have 900 runs together this season. B3$ Just an understanding of where the game is going and what needs to be done. Having an experienced guy who's captained at the international level - it's been a beautiful transition for us coming together for RCB at the top and making an impact. Crowd here was amazing today as well. Told Faf as well. Just felt like it was a home game for us. They were cheering for us, taking my name as well. I feel you can't create this. I haven't forced anyone to follow me or be inspired by me. I'm just myself on the field. I do everything on the field very honestly and I think that resonates with people. It's an amazing position to be in that you can provide happiness to so many people. That's something I love to see when they have a smile on their face when I perform.

commText: As far as both teams are concerned. There are respective concerns which have been highlighted over the course of the tournament. RCB have had issues finishing an innings. But Anuj Rawat's last over assault in the last game came across like a fresh breeze for the RCB team and that helped them to grapple the momentum by the end of the innings. SRH have had a hit and a miss season in both departments.

Will SRH rain on RCB's parade? That's the big question of the hour after DC's win against PBKS. SRH are eliminated. But RCB need to string two wins to think of a place in the top four. If they falter, things would be very tough for them. If they lose, CSK and LSG would be through. So expect the loyal fanbases to get behind SRH. Even MI fans would be backing SRH as that would ensure they have lesser competition.

B0$ Only six league matches to go and there are still as many as seven teams vying for the remaining three playoff spots. Not all of them are in control of their own fate. RCB, though, do have things in their own hands given their superior NRR, and stand a good chance of going through if they win their next two matches. So it's all to play for today as they take on Sunrisers Hyderabad in Hyderabad - a venue where the visitors have won just once in 7 matches. Hello and welcome to our live coverage.

B0$ 
 
Unlike in a season of football around the world, IPL offers no real easy, lopsided fixture. It's just the nature of the sport and the quality - on paper, at the very least - across the 10 teams. Yet, RCB should head to Hyderabad with renewed hope knowing that they take on a side that has struggled for cohesion all season and whose campaign has already come to a disappointing and premature end. 
 
The renewed hope also stems from RCB's statement win over Rajasthan Royals from three nights ago that hit two birds with one stone for Faf du Plessis's side - dent a fellow top-four aspirant and gain a massive NRR boost. A win on Thursday will take RCB to 14 points and give them the advantage of knowing what exactly they need to do next to make it through to the playoffs as their last game is the final league game of the season. Long story, short - the ball is still very much in their court. 
 
For all to go to plan, RCB need a bright start with the ball. They have the worst ER in the middle and the death overs but are effective in the first six, having picked the most wickets in that phase this season (30). They could truly dictate terms with consistency in this period as SRH have been shaky starters, with the second worst run rate in the batting PowerPlay, and the least boundary count (85 - 74 fours, 11 sixes). A lot of such numbers for SRH flatter to deceive because of how their overall season has been - massively underwhelming. Head coach Brian Lara has rued the multiple defeats they've endured from clearly winnable scenarios, and the fact that the team missed being much higher on the points table. That ship has now sailed, but even when there's nothing to play for, they could derail RCB's campaign and strive to avoid the ignominy of earning the wooden spoon.
